        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Infowars sale</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/ps-dec-12-2.jpg" alt="Infowars sale" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px);">A bankruptcy judge <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2024/12/11/media/infowars-onion-lawsuit-block-hnk-intl/index.html" target="_blank">blocked</a> The Onion’s bid for Alex Jones’ Infowars platform, citing flaws in the auction process that failed to maximize value. Judge Christopher Lopez expressed concern about transitioning from a live auction to sealed bids. <a href="https://theonion.com/" target="_blank">The Onion</a>, backed by <a href="https://apnews.com/article/onion-buys-infowars-alex-jones-6496f198d141c991087dcd937b3588e9" target="_blank">Sandy Hook victims’ families</a>, offered $1.75 million in cash, valued at $7 million, while First United American Companies, linked to Jones, bid $3.5 million.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px);">
          Although the judge found no fault with The Onion’s bid, he criticized the auction handling and ordered the trustee to reconsider the process without reopening the auction. Jones, facing nearly <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/dec/07/alex-jones-infowars-bankruptcy" target="_blank">$1.5 billion</a> in defamation damages, celebrated the ruling as the “right thing.” Jones had used Infowars to spread conspiracy theories into public disclosure.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
